public class TeamRepositoryException
extends java.lang.Exception

Exception indicating a failure involving a repository. This is the primary exception thrown by methods in the Jazz Platform.

Guidelines on Use of Exceptions at the Client API

Most Client API operations (ITeamRepository and friends) can throw both checked and unchecked exceptions.

How the Client API uses checked exceptions

Methods of the Client API are declared to throw the checked exception TeamRepositoryException. TeamRepositoryException is an API class, and the operations that throw this exception explain the general conditions under which the exception is thrown.

TeamRepositoryException is subclassed directly off Exception, making it unrelated to IOException or any other specific pool of checked exceptions.

TeamRepositoryException is a general-purpose exception. Programmatically, the only information available with a TeamRepositoryException is its origin and some attached data, but event that information is optional and cannot be guaranteed in all situations.

There are number of error conditions that client code can sometimes meaningfully handle is as special cases. Specialized subclasses of TeamRepositoryException are used to report these conditions. For example, if the client is not logged in to the repository, the API operations throw NotLoggedInException. This allows clients to catch this specific exception and attempt to log-in. Specialized subclasses of TeamRepositoryException may carry additional data. For example, ItemNotFoundException carries the handle of the missing item.

The API operations that may report specific conditions are spec'd to throw the specialized subclass for that situation (and may mention that exception in the throws clause in addition to TeamRepositoryException; this is just a convenience for documenting, and has no effect on source or binary compatibility).

Catching TeamRepositoryException

Catching a specialized subclass of TeamRepositoryException in the immediate vicinity of an operation that throws that exception is commonplace; this is generally how the client intercepts particular conditions that they can treat.

Catching TeamRepositoryException in order to wrap it in some other exception class is commonplace; this is generally how the client converts an arbitrary repository-specific condition into their own exception class.

However, "eating" a TeamRepositoryException is generally not recommended, as this practice hides failures and tends to make programs very hard to debug, as well as being unhelpful to the end user who usually needs to know when there are problems talking to the server.

Catching a TeamRepositoryException, setting its origin, and re-throwing it is not a problem. This is the common pattern for ensuring that an exception thrown by an operation carries an indication of the repository involved.

Instantiating TeamRepositoryException

Normal clients of the Client API are discouraged from creating and throwing new instances of TeamRepositoryException or its subclasses. They should instead declare their own checked exception type (unrelated to TeamRepositoryException) and throw it instead.

Client libraries (i.e., the client-side layer that implements the a component's Client API) are free to create instances of TeamRepositoryException or its API subclasses provided that they are visible to that client library (i.e., belong to the component's client library, or are declared as API exceptions in a required component's common plug-in).

Service implementations (i.e., server-side code that implements a component's service interface) are free to create instances of TeamRepositoryException or its API subclasses provided that they are visible to that service implementation (i.e., belong to the component's client library, or are declared as API exceptions in a required component's common plug-in).

Subclassing TeamRepositoryException

Clients of the Client API are discouraged from declaring their own exceptions subclasses anywhere under TeamRepositoryException. These exceptions are intended to capture conditions that arise in operation at the Client API. Clients sitting atop the Client API should instead declare their own checked exception type (unrelated to TeamRepositoryException) and throw it instead.

Client libraries are free to declare subclasses of TeamRepositoryException or its API subclasses provided that they are visible to that client library.

Service implementations are free to create instances of TeamRepositoryException or its API subclasses provided that they are visible to that service implementation.

Messages on TeamRepositoryException

All instances of TeamRepositoryException or subclasses must have a help message string. This message is in English.

The exceptions instances may originate either in client-side code or on the server. They arise in the context of a particular operation at the Client API, which is somewhat low-level.

The purpose of this message is to aid Java developers working with client-side code that calls methods on the Client API, or server-side code that calls the service interfaces. These error messages are unsuitable for presenting to an end user under normal (as opposed to emergency) situations. In this respect, the messages on checked exceptions are no different from those on unchecked exceptions.

Explaining checked exceptions to an end user

If the client code calling the Client API operation wishes to present a particular TeamRepositoryException instance to the end user, they are entirely responsible for doing so, including message localization.

The recommended wording for a generic TeamRepositoryException is "Unexpected repository error". Each of the specific subclasses gives a suggested wording in the class comment.

The Client API and server implementation do not have message catalogs.

Logging unexpected conditions on the server

From time to time things will go badly on the server in ways that are unexpected. For the server, "unexpected" means that these conditions are not expected to occur, even in the presence of badly behaving clients. That a client asks to fetch an item that is not present in the repository, or attempts to modify a change set that is not active in their workspace, are conditions that are expected. Unexpected conditions are things like a call to the database mediator reporting that a column with a certain name is missing, or an assertion failure in the bowels of server-side code.

Expected error conditions should not be logged on the server. They should be reported back to the client.

Unexpected error conditions should be logged on the server. They should also be reported back to the client, normally as an InternalRepositoryException. The error message should include the timestamp of the server's log entry, so that it's feasible for service personnel to later correlate the unexpected failure that the end user saw with the server log. Example message:

Internal error: Assertion failure in !LocalRepositoryServiceImpl.internalAccept.
See server log entry 20051201170512

How the Client API uses unchecked exceptions

The implementations of the Client API operations throw RuntimeExceptions for various conditions, including most cases of "pilot error" where the client gets caught doing something that they had been told never to do, like passing null for a parameter. The conditions that the client needs to avoid are flagged in the spec with "must"; e.g., a parameter that "must not be null".

All bets are off if a client does any of the things that they have been told they must not do. In practice, the client API is most helpful when it can inexpensively detect such violations and pull the plug by throwing some kind of RuntimeException. In general, it not a contractually specified behavior of a method that it throws RuntimeException for such violations; rather it is a helpful implementation that is consistent with the specification.

It would be a programming error for a client to depend on the implementation throwing one of these exceptions. By the same token, it would be equally bad practice for a client to depend on the implementation not throwing one of these exceptions.
